You can achieve this by controlling the row selection state and updating the `rowSelection` and `rowClassName` props of the Ant Design Table. I'll walk you through the steps.

1. Create a state variable to hold the currently selected bank:

```javascript
const [selectedBank, setSelectedBank] = useState(null);
```

2. Update the `onChange` function in the `rowSelection` prop to store the selected bank and filter the rows accordingly:

```javascript
const rowSelection = {
  onChange: (selectedRowKeys, selectedRows) => {
    if (selectedRows.length > 0) {
      setSelectedBank(selectedRows[0].bank);
    } else {
      setSelectedBank(null);
    }
  },
  getCheckboxProps: (record) => ({
    disabled: selectedBank !== null && record.bank !== selectedBank,
  }),
};
```

Here, we use the `getCheckboxProps` function to disable rows based on the selected bank.

3. Set the `rowClassName` prop to apply a different className based on the selected state:

```javascript
const rowClassName = (record) => {
  return selectedBank !== null && record.bank !== selectedBank
    ? "disabled-row"
    : "";
};
```

4. Apply the `rowSelection` and `rowClassName` props to the Ant Design Table component:

```javascript
<Table
  rowSelection={rowSelection}
  rowClassName={rowClassName}
  columns={columns}
  dataSource={data}
/>
```

5. Style the disabled rows if necessary. Add the following CSS to apply a different background color for  disabled rows:

```css
.disabled-row {
  background-color: #f5f5f5;
  pointer-events: none;
}
```

Here is a working example of the complete solution:

```javascript
import React, { useState } from "react";
import { Table } from "antd";
import "antd/dist/antd.css";
import "./styles.css";

export default function App() {
  const [selectedBank, setSelectedBank] = useState(null);

  const rowSelection = {
    onChange: (selectedRowKeys, selectedRows) => {
      if (selectedRows.length > 0) {
        setSelectedBank(selectedRows[0].bank);
      } else {
        setSelectedBank(null);
      }
    },
    getCheckboxProps: (record) => ({
      disabled: selectedBank !== null && record.bank !== selectedBank,
    }),
  };

  const rowClassName = (record) => {
    return selectedBank !== null && record.bank !== selectedBank
      ? "disabled-row"
      : "";
  };

  const columns = [
    {
      title: "ID",
      dataIndex: "id",
    },
    {
      title: "Bank",
      dataIndex: "bank",
    },
  ];

  const data = [
    {
      key: "1",
      id: "1",
      bank: "agricola",
    },
    {
      key: "2",
      id: "2",
      bank: "agricola",
    },
    {
      key: "3",
      id: "3",
      bank: "other",
    },
    {
      key: "4",
      id: "4",
      bank: "other",
    },
  ];

  return (
    <div className="App">
      <Table
        rowSelection={rowSelection}
        rowClassName={rowClassName}
        columns={columns}
        dataSource={data}
      />
    </div>
  );
}
```

Now, when you select a row with a specific `bank`, all other rows with different `bank` values will be disabled, and you can only select rows with matching bank values. When no rows are selected, all rows will be enabled again.

To achieve this, you can modify the `onChange` function and the condition in `getCheckboxProps`:

1. Update the `onChange` function in the `rowSelection` prop to enable/disable other rows based on the presence of a selected row with `bank` equal to "agricola":

```javascript
const rowSelection = {
  onChange: (selectedRowKeys, selectedRows) => {
    if (selectedRows.some(row => row.bank === "agricola")) {
      setSelectedBank("agricola");
    } else {
      setSelectedBank(null);
    }
  },
  getCheckboxProps: (record) => ({
    disabled:
      (selectedBank === "agricola" && record.bank !== "agricola") ||
      (selectedBank !== "agricola" && selectedBank !== null && record.bank === "agricola"),
  }),
};
```

This will only disable other banks when a row with `bank` equal to "agricola" is selected. When selecting other banks, it will disable the records with `bank` equal to "agricola".

